            <div type="translation">
                <p>Κύριε βοήθει Ἀλεξίῳ μοναχῷ / ἀρχιεπισκόπῳ Κύπρου καὶ συγκέλλῳ.</p>
                <p xml:lang="en">Lord, help the monk Alexios, archbishop of Cyprus and <hi rend="italic">synkellos</hi>.</p>
                <p xml:lang="de">Herr, hilf dem Mönch Alexios, Erzbischof von Zypern und <hi rend="italic">synkellos</hi>.</p>
              </div>
            <div type="commentary" subtype="text">
                <p>As the seal has a very high degree of damage and corrosion, the reading of the inscription was only possible through surface analysis with the RTI technique and a further comparison with the specimen M-8369 from the State Hermitage Museum.[1] General palaeographic features of the inscription suggest a date in the late 11th century. As Georgiou points out in an essay which is in part devoted to M-8369,[2] an archbishop of Cyprus named Alexios – who may be identical with the owner of the seals – is mentioned in several synodika of the church of Cyprus, where he is sometimes listed between the archbishops Basileios (end of the 11th century)[3] and Nicholas Muzalon (archbishop in Cyprus in 1107-1110),[4] and sometimes before both of them.</p>
              </div>
